observations.recommendation:
The Municipal Accountant and the GSO, prepare and maintain the required PCs and PPELC for each category of PPE;

The General Services and Accounting Offices complete the physical count of its properties including real property accounts and conduct reconciliation thereof; 

The Municipal Mayor create the Disposal Committee to initiate the immediate disposal of the unserviceable properties; and

The Municipal Accountant fast track the assessment of ascertaining the recoverable service amount of the assets, and thereafter, set up the allowance for impairment consistent with the requirements of IPSAS 21, to present fairly the PPE accounts in the financial statements to arrive at reliable PPE balances.

The Municipal Mayor instruct the Supply Officer and the Municipal Accountant to (i) reconcile the discrepancy between the book balance and the physical count report of the Office Supplies Inventory account, and (ii) make the necessary adjusting entries in their respective records;

 Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of inventories for the first and second semesters and prepare the report to be submitted to the Audit Team not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year, respectively;

Supply Office and the Accounting Office maintain SC and SLC, respectively, for each type of supply to record all receipts and issuances.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendation and the Management agreed to:
Prepare and maintain the required PPELCs and PCs for each category of PPE;
Complete the physical count of its properties including real property accounts and conduct reconciliation thereof;
Create the Disposal Committee and initiate the immediate disposal of the unserviceable properties pursuant to Section 162 of COA Circular 92-386; and
Create an Inventory Committee to fast track compliance with COA Circular 2020-006 to establish the cost of the actual and existing PPE items and consequently provide the correct accumulated depreciation and/or accumulated impairment loss in the financial statements.

Management submit the request/s by the end user to the BAC or the HoPE identifying the emergency sought to be addressed, and the necessary goods that must be procured to address the emergency; 

 submit revised and approved Annual Procurement Plan showing the subject purchases and their procurement method used; 

 submit justification on the deficiencies noted on the (i) Purchase Orders, (ii) Requisition and Issue Slips, (iii) Acceptance and Inspection Reports and (iv) the BAC Recommendation and Award resolutions; and 

 submit information on the estimates as to the number of meals prepared for the ingredients/raw materials purchased and the recipients thereof.

We reiterated our recommendation and the LCE agreed to direct the 

(a) Municipal Accountant to cancel the stale checks and restore in the books the balances of corresponding cash and liability accounts; 

(b) provide the necessary documents to support the recorded adjusting entries; 

(c) record the above-noted reconciling items and errors based on competent documents; and 

(d) Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to coordinate in locating the documents pertaining to said reconciling items

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the: 

(a) Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary adjusting/ correcting entries for the following errors: (i) misstatement of amounts set up for RPT and SET Receivables for CY 2022; 

(ii) understatement of SL postings; and (iii) unrecorded collection of RPT Receivable; 

(b) Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to regularly reconcile their reciprocal data on RPT and SET Receivables; and 

(c) Municipal Treasurer to (i) prepare the data necessary in the computation of the RPT Target Collections based on the formula provided by the BLGF; and 

(ii) strategize specifically on how to collect from delinquent taxpayers and, if warranted, enforce the provision of Section 254(b) of the RA 7160 in the collection of delinquent taxes.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the 

(a) Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of PPEs and submit the report on the result thereof; 

(b) the Municipal Accountant and the designated Property Officer to maintain a complete and correct records and reports for PPEs; and 

(c) Accounting Office to (i) check the correctness of the application of depreciation; 

(ii) reconcile the balances of acquisition cost and accumulated depreciation between lapsing schedule and Subsidiary Ledgers; 

(iii) determine the need for impairment for PPEs and draw adjusting entries, if warranted; 

(iv) identify the items comprising the beginning balances of noted PPE class; 

(v) draw the necessary adjusting entries to reclassify PPE items in their appropriate classification; and 

(vi) in coordination with GSO complete the required details on every PPE items. We also advised that the LCE convene a Disposal Committee that will facilitate the disposal of unserviceable/obsolete properties in accordance with the prescribed procedures.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the 

(a) HRMO and heads of the offices concerned to (i) identify the specific needs for JOs, Casuals and CoS; 

(ii) define in the contract the service contractors’ duties and responsibilities;

(iii) require all the JOs, CoS, Casuals and Consultants to regularly submit their accomplishment reports; and 

(iv) submit a copy of said contract to the Office of the Auditor within the prescribed period; and 

(b) Municipal Accountant to strengthen his review function on the requisite documents on payment of allowance/honoraria to JOs, Casuals, CoS and Consultants.

To Municipal Accountant:
1. Trace, record, and adjust the affected PPE accounts of the noted differences, especially the demolished and
unserviceable difference;
To Municipal Gen. Service Officer:
2. Expedite the disposal of the above-mentioned unserviceable properties to reflect the accurate and reliable amount
of the PPE account;
3. Identify the accountable officers over the lost properties/not existing items and require the filing of the Request
from Relief of Accountability;

1. Direct the Inventory Committee to strategize the conduct of complete physical inventory taking of all the assets and properties of the LGU and submit updated RPCPPE to the auditor not later than January 31 of each year in reported compliance with the existing rules and regulations; and (2) the highest standards of honesty, objectivity and consistency shall be observed in the keeping of accounts to safeguard against inaccurate or misleading information;
2. Direct the Inventory Committee to ensure that the reconciliation process between the physical inventory records of the MGSO and accounting records are properly in placed, to come up with a reliable report.
3. Require the Municipal General Services Officer to maintain complete and updated property cards to facilitate periodic reconciliation with the Accounting unit;
4. Direct the Municipal General Services Officer to locate documents pertinent to the LGU properties preparatory to the conduct of the mandatory physical inventory;
5. Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical count of all properties including those distributed in the barangays and schools in accordance with existing regulations in order to establish actual existence;
6. Request the MGSO to timely submit updated RPCPPE to the accounting office to facilitate reconciliation with the latter’s property ledger and to reflect the correct balance of the PPE accounts in the financial statements;
7. Make appropriate and necessary adjustments in the books of accounts.

The Municipal Accountant to:
1. Regularly prepare the bank reconciliation statement of all depository accounts and furnish the Municipal Treasurer and COA Auditor a copy with bank statements, JEV reconciling items as well as a copy of the letter to the respective bank informing them of errors noted in the BRS (other than those resulting from the timing of recording of transactions);
2. Prepare journal entry voucher for the cancellation and reversion of stale checks, set up receivable from payor whose check was subsequently returned and record deposit on letters of credit, financial expenses and other valid reconciling items;
The Municipal Treasurer to:
3. Refund the amount of P3,200.00 for the bank service charge incurred due to insufficient funds. Hence monitor regularly the cash balances and close depository accounts in which the purpose had already been satisfied to avoid possible dormancy charges or below maintaining balance bank charges.

1. Direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct regular monitoring and analysis of receivable accounts to ensure that these are collected when these become due and demandable and that cash advances and fund transfers are liquidated within the prescribed period depending upon their nature and purpose;
2. Continue exerting efforts to collect the overdue receivables;
3. File request for authority to write-off dormant accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 and direct Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to gather documents in support of the write-off request.

1. Direct the MEO to exert effort in tracing the program of works (POW) for the construction of line canal at Barangay Poblacion. In case of failure to locate the records, evaluate the necessity and propriety of the project and consider reprogramming the idle funds to other LDRRM priority PPAs;
2. Henceforth, establish proper monitoring of all projects being implemented by the LGU and ensure that no projects are being overlooked;
3. Direct the LDRRM officer to include savings from completed projects in the preparation of LDRRMFIP.

1. Cope up with the prior years’ backlogs and ensure that POW and Detailed Engineering Estimates are promptly prepared to facilitate implementation of the projects within the targeted dates;
2. Conduct comprehensive analysis of funding sources and ensure that PPAs are properly linked with those sources and service delivery outcomes, prioritize projects which are ready for implementation for constituents to enjoy the benefits at the earliest opportunity;
3. Ensure optimal utilization of the 20% LDF pursuant to the intent of DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017 by prioritizing the PPAs which are attainable.

1. Direct the BAC to address immediately the lengthy and delayed deliveries of detailed documents;
2. Expedite the release and approval of the documents, especially the necessary documents to cause the delivery of procured items;
3. Direct the concerned departments to conduct time and motion study in the procurement process in order to identify areas/problems relative to the delay in the process and come up with possible recommendations and actions to address the problems.

